# Project Overview

This is a **TikTok-style instant messaging (IM) high-fidelity prototyping project** built with Next.js + React as a single-page application (SPA), using 390px iPhone design width with proportional scaling.

**Prototyping principles:**
- If a **Figma design** is provided, you must **pixel-perfectly reproduce the Figma design** (pixel-level alignment, property-by-property matching)
- If only **verbal/text description** is given (no Figma), do your best to reproduce the described interaction and visual effects

### Implemented Pages

> **Maintenance rule: Every time a new feature is merged into the main branch, this section must be updated.**
> Also update the corresponding section in `CLAUDE.md` to keep both rule files in sync.

**Inbox Page**
- Top nav bar (new message, filter, search)
- Stories horizontal scroll bar
- Notification cells (new followers, activity, system notifications, each with unique icons and colors)
- DM conversation list (avatar + story ring + online green dot + streak flame + unread badge + message preview + timestamp)
- Bottom Tab bar (5 tabs)

**Chat Page**
- Nav bar (back, avatar, nickname, online status, streak flame, action buttons)
- Message list (auto-scroll to bottom, time stamps by interval, consecutive message corner merging)
- Message types: text bubble, pure emoji large text, sticker, image, shared post, video
- Text input bar (auto-expand multi-line input, multiple button state switching)
- Long-press message: reaction emoji picker (7 emoji + animation) + context menu (reply/forward/copy/delete/report)
- Reaction bubbles: spring animation below messages
- Emoji & sticker panel (emoji inserts into input, sticker sends directly, favorites page)
- Album panel (3-column photo grid, multi-select numbering, Send button, sends as image messages)
- Read receipt ("Seen")
- Delete message animation (scale + opacity + height collapse)

## Layout Scaling Rule

All pages use a **design-width-based proportional scaling** strategy to ensure pixel-perfect rendering across any screen size.

- **Design width**: `390px` (iPhone standard)
- **Scale factor**: `scale = viewportWidth / 390`
- **Design height**: `designHeight = viewportHeight / scale`
- **Transform origin**: `top left`

The page is rendered at a fixed 390px width with all elements at design-time sizes, then `transform: scale()` is applied to the outer container to fit the viewport.

```tsx
const DESIGN_WIDTH = 390;

const scale = window.innerWidth / DESIGN_WIDTH;
const designHeight = window.innerHeight / scale;

<div style={{
  width: DESIGN_WIDTH,
  height: designHeight,
  transform: `scale(${scale})`,
  transformOrigin: "top left",
}}>
```

**Do not** use responsive breakpoints or fluid sizing (e.g. `max-w-[480px]`, percentage widths) for page layout. All new pages should follow this scaling pattern.

## NPM / Node Version & Registry

This project deploys on **v0 / Vercel**. Node.js >= 20, npm >= 10.

### Public registry

Always use the **public npm registry** to avoid lockfile pollution from internal registries:

```bash
npm install <package> --registry=https://registry.npmjs.org
```

This ensures `package-lock.json` contains public `resolved` URLs, which is required for v0/Vercel deployment to work correctly.

After installing, verify no internal URLs leaked into the lockfile:

```bash
grep -c "registry.npmmirror\|bytedance\|bnpm" package-lock.json
# Should output: 0
```
